				<span class="postdetails">
					<br /><b>Joined:</b> Mon Jul 18, 2011 10:04 pm<br /><b>Posts:</b> 24
				</span>

			</td>
			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I'm going to try and squeeze a 2mb game into 512k. That might be difficult, however. I would like as much space as I can get because I can run a real risk of running out. (FYI, the actual PSX FF7 engine is 4MB, but that also includes some game data embedded in it.)</div><br />The playstation has 2MB system RAM.... I doubt the kernel is 4MB.<br /></div><br /><br />The core kernel of the PSX version was a little under a meg.. it sat about the 700k mark. The game banked in several engines from the CD-ROM depending on the game state. The kernel actually would load modules in the background while you played the game and then switched to that gamestate when needed. The modules were menu, field, world map, battle, and minigame. The PC port did away with the module swap and just compiled it all together into a 4MB executable. Things like the menu layout, which used to be a separate module in the PSX was integrated into the executable itself in the PC version, so the engine was about 4 meg, the kernel that ran the show was much less. The point I was making was FF7 took up three CD-ROMS, but the full engine  in relation is quite tiny. (and on all three disks) <br /><br />All final fantasies do this, including the first one. The first had a kernel, an aux kernel, battle, field, overworld, and dungeon. <br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">* The save ram can get a little heavy. An actual FF7 PSX save is a touch over 4k. However there is a lot of irrelevant info in there when moving to NES-Space and can be cut in half.</div><br />A touch over 4k ? Since a playstation memory card save is 8k, exactly like the standard size of a NES battery save, I guess half of it is unused on FF7 saves then ?</div>
<br />
<br />The FF7 <a href="http://wiki.qhimm.com/FF7/Savemap" class="postlink">savemap</a> is 0x10ED bytes (4333 bytes) long, minus the header info.  Most of that is a save of the main work memory for the game which is irrelevant when porting to the NES. 
<br />
<br />In the end, it's a complete waste of time. I agree. But it's also a hobby, which by definition, is a *supposed* to be a complete waste of time. I have no problems poking at the idea with a stick. Take a look at the guy who ported Halo to the 2600. 
<br />
<br />What happened was I was watching some romhacking guys do some gorgeous stuff with the FF7 nes version, and thought as a neat programming exercise  and to oblige them with a better engine. Because I've never done 6502 machine code outside of reversing and rewriting small programs. I'd thought I would take it up a notch.
<br />
<br />However, I've never really worked with the NES architecture before. I'm no stranger to 6502 code, and I do projects in C# all the time, but while getting down to the nuts and bolts of it, I'm not sure on all the mappers yet, and I'm unfamiliar with the linker. Most of my 6502 code has really just been one-shot less than 16k stuff. I need a good bank-switching template and a mapper that fits my needs. I'll hammer everything out as I learn. Heck, my first thing to do is to make a squaresoft logo, and then see of I can draw a static menu page, pulling variables from ram. I'm nowhere near even making a map yet.
<br />
<br />And... I've thinking about doing a project like this for several years. It just when the FF7NES romhacking thing came to life, I decided to give it a shot.
<br />
<br />Anywho... Back on subject...
<br />
<br />Here's a rundown of mappers I have found
<br />
<br />-UxROM - Out due to lack of RAM
<br />-BNROM Out due to lack of RAM
<br />-MMC3 - The 245 Mapper variant gives me 1MB and a sexy scanline IRQ (In FF7, the battle menu takes up the bottom of the screen, this might be useful!)
<br />-MMC5 - 1MB, but waaay to much going on. 
<br />-SxROM If Both CHR 0 and CHR 1 are supported, this gives me 1MB on an MMC1 mapper. I'll experiment with this configuration tonight and see if emulators support that.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

